      "Last week Unify's sales team had an offsite in Nashville, and the energy was incredible. The team ended June at 140% to goal, capping off our best month on record.\n \nOur revenue team is split between SF and NYC and the offsite was a great bonding experience for everyone. Being in person together matters.\n \nThe last few months haven't been easy on our sales team. We made a ton of changes after a strong December/January run, and selling Unify got harder starting in February.\n \nBut now we're hitting our stride again, and Nashville felt like a crescendo of that momentum. We rolled out a new pitch deck, two new sales methodologies, and everyone showed up focused on one question: \"how can I be better?\"\n \n--\n2 key points stuck with me when I was reflecting on the trip:\n \n(1) Change is constant\n \nIf you're working at a startup expecting consistency, you're in the wrong place. Our go-to-market motion has evolved so much over the past 12 months. A year ago, our revenue team was myself, Skyler and Tameem. We had 20 people at this offsite, it was a completely different world.\n \nOur go-to-market motion requires us to keep evolving and leveling up as our product does. Our team embraces this.\n \n(2) Inputs \u003E outputs\n \nWhen your team focuses on inputs, the outputs take care of themselves. Yes, quota and revenue closed matter. But focusing on what you can control (the inputs) is what's necessary to find step-function changes.\n \nRight now our team is laser focused on improving our win rate via enablement, training and better osmosis of what tactics are working. We believe that we can 2x+ our win rates, June was a great early indicator of that.\n \nNashville was awesome. We ate too much brisket. Anthony won at go-karting. Skyler wore sunglasses at night.\n \nUnified team unified dream. Excited for this next chapter for our revenue team 🚀",
