      "This week the Unify NYC team is moving into to our 1st dedicated NYC office at 665 Broadway. I get asked often if being bicoastal between SF and NYC is worth it.\n \nHonest answer: It's complicated, but the benefits have outweigh the challenges. Here's why we decided to do it and what it's meant for Unify.\n\nStartups are all about talent, and we intentionally decided to bet on being bi-costal because we believed it would allow us to recruit the best talent.\n \nIn 2023 as a seed stage company, we did everything we could to get the best talent to join the team. Hyewon, our Design Lead, and Fabian, our Eng Lead, were in NYC and couldn't move. If we wanted our team to be SF only, we never could have hired them.\n \nSo we set up a shared office space that we've been consistently expanding as our team has grown in 2024 and 2025.\n \nHaving a New York presence has absolutely helped us to land talent across product and go-to-market. Today our NYC team is the same size as our SF one.\n \nHaving a sales presence on the east coast also matters, nothing beats selling in person.\n \nBut there's absolutely friction that comes from having 2 offices:\n(1) Costs: 2 offices, travel back and forth, it all adds up. It's cheaper to have one HQ\n(2) Culture: we've tried to be maniacal about trying to maintain our culture, and keeping the core values consistent across both offices. But doing so takes serious effort from the founders. This means that Connor and I are traveling often and spend a lot of time in our NYC office\n \nIf I could migrate everyone to a single office, I 100% would, but that's not realistic, and not the best thing for Unify.\n \nWe're stoked to be moving into 665 Broadway, with it we're entering a new chapter of the Unify story.",
