    postContent:
      "If you're a Series B-D founder in 2025, the right growth leader will inflect your business. Here are the 4 things you should look for in a potential hire:\n\n(1) Unorthodox backgrounds\n\nYou're not looking for traditional marketers. You want analytical problem-solvers who are first principles thinkers. You want someone who sees growth as a science to be tested and iterated on. You want to hire future founders.\n\nOur Growth Lead Rhea had zero marketing background. Her background (Bridgewater Associates + Kalshi) was unorthodox. \n\n(2) Deep understanding of unit economics\n \nGrowth leaders are constantly making go/no-go decisions based on unit economics. Unit economics are a guiding force in startups. Great growth operators have strong business intuition for if a bet is worth taking based on the economics.\n\nI prefer CAC payback period as my north star for unit economics. As a rule of thumb, \u003C12 months is great, 12-24 months is okay, 24+ months and you need to improve.\n\nSome operators I've seen who've mastered this:\nDennis Sevilla - COO & CFO at Guru\nMax Beauroyre - Head of Growth at Abacum\nEdouard U. - Growth Lead at Pigment\n\n(3) Xfn skills\n \nGrowth sits at the intersection of sales, product, and engineering – teams with very different priorities. Great growth operators can work across these functions seamlessly to deliver impact. It's simple, but not easy to find in practice.\n\n(4) Experimentation and data driven\n \nDiving into pivot tables, SQL queries and dashboards should be second nature. The right candidates will want to validate every decision with data.\n\nIn my experience growth experiments fail 2 out of 3 times. The best operators double down on the winners to squeeze them for every ounce of output. And they see the shimmers of hope in the experiment that failed for the wrong reason.\n\nA great growth leader is your next 10x hire. Go find them!",
