      "I turn away sponsors for 3 main reasons:\n\n🌱 I wouldn’t organically recommend the product\n💳 The terms or comp don't align \n🔬 They try to micromanage what I say—and hurt themselves in the process\n\nSo I felt very seen reading Typeform’s Get Real report on influencer marketing.\nOne finding really stuck: “Let the influencer cook.”\n\nNow, I don’t cook at all—so I was a little concerned at first. But I then realized it means when you hire influencers, don’t micromanage them. Let them go, run, fly, do their thing, [insert metaphor of choice].\n\nI write all the copy for my newsletter and LinkedIn posts. It’s in my voice, with my frameworks, for my audience.\n\nWhen a brand sends over rigid phrasing or messaging that clearly doesn’t fit, I pass. Because it won’t work—for either of us.\n\nThe whole point of partnering with creators isn’t to make them sound like your comms team. It’s to tap into their voice, their trust, their POV.\n\nWhen that gets edited out, so does the influence.\n\nFull report (worth a read): \nhttps://lnkd.in/epFvvxci",
