      'What if you made no new big content for the next 6 months?\nSounds like bad advice, right?\n\nBut this is a thought experiment I run with almost every growth- and late-stage company I work with:\n👉 "If you published no brand new content, what would your social calendar look like?"\n\nMost teams say something like:\n“We actually have enough content to keep going for 6+ months. We have so many things we haven\'t distributed well. But we’re not allowed to do that"\n\nSo I ask: "Why not?"\n\n🥛 If you already have high-quality content that hasn’t been fully distributed or repurposed, why wouldn’t you repurpose and distribute—doubling down on what\'s worked?\n🧗‍♂️  It’s often riskier to chase new ideas than it is to double down on the content that’s already working.\n⏳ New content takes time, budget, and coordination\n\nSo the next time you’re pitching a big new content project, ask:\nIs this truly additive and uniquely valuable?\n\nIf not, your default should probably be “no”\n\n🛑 And should you really make no new content for 6 months? Probably not, but maybe pare back your brand new content calendar considerably. And if nothing else this thought experiment makes you really think hard about what you have made, and what you haven\'t distributed.\n\n⬇️ More suggestions on improving your content process in my latest MKT1 newsletter series: "A behind the scenes look at the MKT1 content strategy"',
