      "One of the best decisions we made with the GTM Engineer School's go-to-market? \nLean into organic social.\n\nBack in January, there was no course, no students, no sponsors — just our hypothesis:\n\nGTM teams are changing fast, and there's a new kind of operating role emerging\n↳ The GTM Engineer\n\nJared and I knew the core of the movement was developing here on LinkedIn, so we decided to lean heavily into it as a channel to drive word of mouth, awareness, and ticket sales.\n\nHere’s how we approached it:\n\n→ Every partner who committed to sponsor the course, we'd announce it\n\n→ Every time we hit specific waitlist milestones, we'd write about it\n\n→ Every time we secured a set of teaching assistants, we'd spotlight their profiles\n\n→ For every module of the course, we organized sneak peeks as webinars\n\n→ Every project milestone (eg. website, pricing, ticket sales milestones), we'd post about it\n\n\n\nBut also, we organized cross-promos with:\n\n\n→ Our 25+ amazing instructors and TAs\n\n→ 15+ of the top 1% of GTM advisors, consultants, and operators in the space\n\n→ And even some of our most committed and passionate students!!\n\n__\n\n\nThe TLDR?\n\n→→→ Turn every milestone into a story to share\n→→ Ask for help to relevant people in your network\n→ And don't be afraid of pounding the rock and be consistent\n\nThat momentum helped us sell out the first cohort.\n(and even overbook factoring in scholarships for the most committed students).\n\nNo growth hacks (never believed in those).\nJust a simple work back plan and consistency.\n\n\nDisclaimer: we also ran some targeted outbound and thought leadership ads, but they were the seasoning to the organic LinkedIn \"main dish\".\n\n\nPS. Next week we finish cohort 1, and we're regrouping to iterate on our students' feedback and prepare cohort 2. If you want to join us for that, sign up below ;)",
