      "Time is money — wasting it is...a waste.\nBut what most people don't understand is that:\n\nFor knowledge workers (like us in tech), giving feedback is one of the biggest levers that make up the *value of your time*.\n\nThink about it:\n\nIn tech, you either:\n↳ Creating (code, words, flows, designs, videos, setting up tools)\n↳ Collaborating (ask, collect, and iterate on feedback)\n\nVirtually 100% of everything that is created is shared for feedback/collaboration\n\nIf you're:\n↳ An IC: you probs spend 60% creating, 40% collaborating\n↳ A manager: you probs spend 80% collaborating, 20% creating\n\nThe value of collaboration translates into real money:\n↳ If your avg IC salary is $80k/yr, the value of collaboration is ~$32k/yr\n↳ If your avg manager salary is $150k/yr, the value of collaboration is ~$120k/yr\n\nScale that to (considering a 1:5 manager-to-IC ratio):\n• A 10 people startup: ~$470k/yr\n• A 100 people lower mid-market: ~4.7M/yr\n• A 500 people upper mid-market: ~23M/yr\n\n___\n\nSo if I create a piece of knowledge, then \"ask for feedback\", AND:\n↳ Comments are too diverging, unclear/vague, or non-constructive\n↳ Too diverging = this might be relevant but it's way out of scope\n↳ Non-constructive = leave me thinking \"what would it be better instead?\"\n↳ Unclear = leave me thinking \"what did they mean?\"\n\nThis translates in LOTS OF WASTED TIME/MONEY:\n\n→ Dollar burned from longer feedback loops\n→ Reworks and decision-making latency\n→ Emotional costs of frustration that lead to churn/turnover\n\nLet's say this amount to ~25% of their week's time chasing feedback and re-syncing (Atlassian 2025 study), that's about:\n\n• A 10 people startup: ~$160k/yr\n• A 100 people lower mid-market: ~1.3M/yr\n• A 500 people upper mid-market: ~6.5M/yr\n\n___\n\nInvest in communicating well.\n\nHere's what I try to do every time I give feedback:\n\n1. Be clear/specific: pre-emptively anticipate ancillary/clarification questions\n2. Focus on outcome: give feedback that converge on the team outcome\n3. Use examples: show what good looks like to give directions on your standards \n4. Know when to diverge: keep diverging feedback for upstream brainstorms\n5. Keep tabs on open threads: unblock who rely on your opinions/approval, fast!\n\nGiving proper feedback saves you time and money. \n\nAnd will also make you a more respected, easy-to-work-with IC/manager.\n\nLet's start act like we care, shall we?",
