      "My mind has been blown with the AI use-cases I've seen—or helped implement—in the last 9 months. I'm going to start sharing tactical examples (if there is interest). \n\nThe first concept I want to share more broadly is around building a strong foundational data layer. Which makes sophisticated GTM possible. \n\nThis is ESPECIALLY important when you want to start laying AI, automation, and agents/agentic workflows into your GTM motion. \n\nEverything in GTM downstream of the foundational data layer is impacted by the quality of data, coverage, accuracy and cost of the basic data points and \"rich\" data points (what what you do with said data points). \n\nI've found that this is one area where AI is incredibly good at deploying. \n\nI'm going to have the legend, Andreas Wernicke, walk through a specific case of a data workflow he has built. Here's what we plan to cover: \n\n1/ Why it matters? \n\n- Replaces 233 hours of manual research (~ $10,500 in costs)\n- Highest level of consistency across written company descriptions \n- Built-in verification across multiple data sources\n- Infinitely scalable \n\n2/ How it works (technical details): \n\n- 3 independent research agents using different AI models\n- One reconciliation agent evaluating all outputs \n- JSON schema prompting for structured outputs\n- Dynamic model selection based on task complexity\n- Built-in transparency for human review\n\n*(Clay's meta prompter is becoming so good that it can replace this for many use cases and make building much easier. It's best to try meta prompter first, and use the build strategy here if you need more accuracy)\n\n3/ Custom-built: \n\n- No black box outputs - full reasoning transparency\n- Cost: A few cents per company vs $45/hour manual work \n- Accuracy through agent consensus, not single-point failure\n- Handles edge cases\n\n4/ I'm going to do a live recording showing this off. We're going to cover: \n\n- Multi-agent principles\n- JSON prompting methodology \n- Deep research context building\n- Model selection strategies\n- Data transparency framework\n\nIf you'd be interested in tuning into this (or getting a recording), please Like or Comment so I know the level of interest. \n\nThanks!",
