    postContent:
      "I got lots of asks for an example of a 'good' resume, so I thought I'd brush mine up and share the format that's worked for me throughout my career. \n\nthere isn't a single format that works for everyone - you might need 2 pages, you might need more bullets, you might need more stats, you might need to include publications, etc. \n\n📌 the most important thing is that the person reading it understands where you spike immediately, and that you're answering the questions they'll have about you as quickly as possible. \n\na few best practices that apply to everyone's resume, in my opinion as someone who's read thousands and thousands of resumes for roles: \n\n〰️ make it easy to read. make it easy to read. make it easy to read. \n\n〰️ lead with what makes you stand out from everyone else applying. why should the person reading it want to have a conversation with you to learn more? \n\n〰️ don't use numbers and stats just to fill space - use them to emphasize your greatest strengths and proven ability to drive impact and results\n\n〰️ you don't have to include everything you've ever done - truly! \n\n〰️ make sure the job title or function you're applying for is included somewhere, either in your summary (looking for a role in X) or in a previous job title or description. hiring managers will often filter for inclusion to filter out spray and pray applications. \n\n〰️ if you have a gap in your career from raising a family, taking a mental health break, caring for a loved one, etc., include one line about it. no need to justify - the hiring manager will either accept your gap or they won't - you won't change their mind. \n\n👋hiring managers - what'd I miss? also - the folks reading this post are likely looking for roles, so if you're hiring, comment your JD ♥",
