      "https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7341452764406784000",
    imgUrl: "",
    postContent:
      "welcome back to another edition of ✨I'm reading hundreds of resumes right now, so I'm going to share some unsolicited resume advice✨\n\nDO: \n- list your most recent 2-3 positions and companies clearly. The hirer needs to know what you've been up to, and where - that's the primary initial signal for whether you might be a good fit.\n\n- add 1-2 easy-to-skim bullets for each role about your focus and impact. they're looking for whether you've done adjacent work to what they need to do, and whether you've done it successfully. \n\n- include your linkedin url so the hiring manager can do an easy click out\n\n- instead of a summary, include a bullet or two on anything specific to the role if relevant (ex. willing to relocate, highly related side hustle, demonstrated passion for the area of focus, etc)\n\n- if you have the capacity, email or dm the hiring manager with a short, bulleted note about why you're uniquely qualified for the role\n\nDON'T\n- write a long, opinionated summary paragraph that's obviously the same for every role you apply for\n\n- make the reader hunt for your titles and companies\n\n- email or DM the hiring and ask for a 1:1 call to ask me questions about the role, or 'learn more about what the company is up to'\n\n- include those graphics that show how strong you are at different skills - they're distracting and confusing to interpret\n\nplease let me know if any of this is confusing in the comments. it's really frustrating to see so many high quality candidates whose resumes aren't well formatted, making them easy to miss in the process of reviewing hundreds in a queue.",
