      'Over the past 6 months, the way I’ve used AI the most… is not for writing code, not for drafting slides,  and definitely not for posting on LinkedIn (otherwise I’d be posting a lot more).\n\n🧠  It’s for self-discovery and self-coaching ❤️ .\n– When I feel overwhelmed, it helps me unpack my emotional responses and thinking patterns \n – When I upload my old writing and life choices, it helps me connect the dots and uncover what truly matters to me\n – In tough parenting moments, it educates me to be a better mom\n (you’ll get this once your kids hit their teenage years)\n\nI used to think this was an odd use case for AI. After all, most people on LinkedIn seem to be optimizing prompts, automating workflows, or building agents.\n\nAnd here I am—using it to reflect on myself, parenting, relationships, life, and meaning.\n\nThen I came across this chart from Harvard Business Review.\n\nThe top 3 GenAI use cases in 2025?\n1. Therapy and emotional support\n2. Organizing your life\n3. Finding purpose\n\nMaybe I’m not an outlier after all.\nMaybe the real power of AI isn’t just helping us do more—\nbut helping us become more "human".',
