    type: "Image",
    postContent:
      "🔥 I agree with Bessemer Venture Partners that the Future of B2B AI is Vertical - here is why \n\n1️⃣ Faster Path to Value\nNarrowing down beats going broad. Just look at Synthesia—they started as a LLM for digital avatars but then focused on enterprise L&D to gain traction. Once they nailed that, they expanded into marketing, product demos, and more.\n\nI've seen this pattern over & over again in Ai startups. Instead of marketing a broad technology to solve problems for everyone, startups that focus on a narrow vertical & use case can demonstrate functional & economic value much faster. \n\n2️⃣ Unique Insights & Data are Your Moat\nTech alone isn’t enough. The best AI startups leverage proprietary data and vertical insights to build a moat.\n\nExample? OWKIN in healthcare—they use federated learning to train models on sensitive medical data across hospitals without centralizing it. \n\nIf you’re just using off-the-shelf LLMs with no unique data/insights, expect firece competitions from 100+ other startups. \n\n3️⃣ Avoid the Head-on Battle with Incumbents\nHorizontal SaaS giants are already embedding AI—Slack, Notion, HubSpot, you name it. Competing head-on is a grind.\n\nLook at AI code editors like Cursor and Codium—they’re outperforming GitHub Copilot now, but long-term? GitHub still owns the DevOps workflow, giving them time to catch up. \n\nMeanwhile, Cognition (Devin) isn’t just adding AI to coding—it’s reimagining the workflow entirely, and maybe that's how disruptors can take on the platforms? \n\nThere’s no one-size-fits-all strategy, but vertical AI startups win by solving high-value, domain-specific problems better than anyone else. The best ones don’t just add AI—they rethink workflows from the ground up that were impossible pre-LLM.",
