    postContent:
      "Just because they worked at Google doesn't mean they can help build your startup. I've lost count of how many times I've heard: \"We just raised our series A and hired an engineer from [big tech firm].\"\n\nFounders get excited by the logos. Google. Meta. Apple.\n\nIt looks like a smart hire.\n\nBut here's the reality:\n\nMost people inside those companies are executing a very narrow swim lane.\n\nThey're part of a massive machine... they're not the person who built it.\n\n- The Google engineer who manages ONE account all day?\n- The Meta specialist who only knows internal politics?\n\nThey're cogs in the wheel.\n\nWhen you're post-Series A, you're not hiring for a cog in the wheel.\n\nYou're hiring someone to build the damn wheel. You need:\n- Someone who can make sense of founder-led chaos\n- Someone who can design systems from scratch \n- Someone who can prioritize ruthlessly and move fast\n- Someone who thrives without a playbook\n\nJust because you can afford a big brand hire doesn't mean you should.\n\nYou don't need a resume with a pedigree.\nYou need a builder.\n\nIf they don't ADD to your culture, they're poison.\n\nI don't care if they built half of Google's infrastructure.\n\nIf they're a culture vampire, they'll destroy everything you've built.\n\nHire the scrappy specialists now.\n\nHire the narrow experts later.",
