    postContent:
      "I've published 120 posts in the last 180 days that have garnered 4.1M impressions and 31k engagements. During this time, I've gone from 3K to 22K followers. More importantly, I've booked 800+ meetings, closed deals and raised funds for Virio.\n\nWhy every CEO (or even every business professional) doesn't do this, is beyond me.\n\nSo, in an attempt to encourage you to get started (or do more), here's how I approach LinkedIn differently that makes it easy for me (and may make it easier for you.)\n\n1. I treat content like product development, not marketing\n\nMost people post randomly and hope something sticks. I run calculated experiments with different content pillars and formats, analyze the data, then double down on what works.\n\nJust like finding product-market fit, I was searching for content-market fit - that sweet spot where my content consistently resonates with my target ICP and drives real pipeline. It took months of testing, but once I found it, everything exploded.\n\n2. I focus on top-of-funnel before throwing money at ads\n\nWhile everyone else is burning cash on LinkedIn ads without knowing what works, I perfected my organic content first. You can't scale what you haven't proven organically. I've figured out exactly what messaging and content formats convert my audience, then I have a blueprint worth investing paid dollars behind.\n\n3. I stayed consistent\n\nLinkedIn will give you an initial boost when you start posting, then completely crush your engagement to test if you're serious. My engagement dropped 75% after the first few weeks. I almost quit. But I kept posting every single day through months of what felt like screaming into the void. The breakthrough only came because I survived the algorithm's games and didn't give up when things got hard.\n\nIf more people treated LinkedIn like a place to learn, test, and connect, instead of a stage to sell, we’d all benefit.\n\nIt’s about being consistent, curious, and customer-focused.\n\nThis approach doesn’t require a team or a big budget.\n\nJust a willingness to show up.",
